This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (API 35) — which .NET 10 targets — enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering and fully deprecates `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE`. The fix is to react to **IME window insets** instead.

### Recommended approach

In your **Platforms/Android** folder, add a listener that applies bottom padding when the keyboard appears:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
using Android.App;
using Android.Content.PM;
using Android.OS;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

[Activity(Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme", MainLauncher = true,
          ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.ScreenSize | ConfigChanges.Orientation |
                                 ConfigChanges.UiMode | ConfigChanges.ScreenLayout |
                                 ConfigChanges.SmallestScreenSize | ConfigChanges.Density,
          WindowSoftInputMode = Android.Views.SoftInput.AdjustNothing)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        var rootView = Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;

        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use the larger of keyboard or nav-bar bottom inset
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            view.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

### Key points

| .NET 9 (old) | .NET 10 (new) |
|---|---|
| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` | `SoftInput.AdjustNothing` + IME insets listener |
| Android resizes the window for you | You read `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` and apply padding yourself |

### Why this works

- `AdjustNothing` tells Android **not** to pan or resize — you handle it.
- The insets listener fires whenever the keyboard opens/closes, giving you the exact pixel height.
- Setting bottom padding on the root view pushes your input bar above the keyboard.

If you also need this on **iOS**, it already works by default — iOS `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` in MAUI handles it. If it doesn't, you can set `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect()` and use a similar inset approach with `UIKeyboard.Notifications`.
